@startuml

class WetWell {
  + liquidLevel : Float
  + environmentalConditions : String
}

class WetWellControlSystem {
  + monitorLiquidLevel() : Float
  + reportLiquidLevel() : Float
  + monitorPumpState() : void
  + reportPumpState() : void
  + activateAlarm() : void
  + switchPump(pump : SubmersiblePump, state : Boolean) : void
  + automatedOperation() : void
  + manualOverrideOperation() : void
  + observationalOperation() : void
  + startPumpMotors() : void
  + stopPumpMotors() : void
  + keepTrackMotorRunningState() : void
  + monitorUnauthorizedEntry() : void
  + monitorEnvironmentalConditions() : void
  + monitorPumpPhysicalCondition() : void
  + displayOperationalParameters() : void
  + provideAlarmFeature() : void
  + equalizeRunTime() : void
}

class PumpControlUnit {
  + startSubmersiblePumpMotors() : void
  + stopPumpMotors() : void
  + keepTrackMotorRunningState() : void
  + keepTrackMotorAvailability() : void
  + startAlternativeMotor() : void
  + setAlarmStateHighWaterLevel() : void
  + equalizeRunTimeOnMotorStartStop() : void
  + useLevelSwitchesToStartPumpMotors() : void
  + onExcessMoistureDetected() : void
  + onOverheatDetected() : void
  + shutdownOverheatedMotor() : void
  + monitorPumpingSite() : void
  + recordOperationalParameters() : void
  + provideAlarmFeature() : void
  + displayOperationalParameters() : void
  + monitorAccessDoorEntry() : void
  + activateVisualAlarm() : void
  + activateAudibleAlarm() : void
  + monitorSealLeak() : void
  + handleSealFailure() : void
}

class SubmersiblePump {
  + isRunning : Boolean
}

class PumpMotor {
  + isRunning : Boolean
  + isAvailable : Boolean
}

class MoistureSensor {
  + sealFailureDetected : Boolean
  + detectSealFailure() : Boolean
}

class LevelSwitch {
  + indicatePumpStart() : void
}

class FloatSwitch {
  + thresholdDepth : Float
  + detectDepth(currentDepth : Float) : Boolean
  + triggerPump(pump : SubmersiblePump) : void
  + setAlarmState() : void
}

class ControlDisplayPanel {
  + depthOfInfluent : Float
  + displayDepth(depth : Float) : void
  + displayOperationalParameters() : void
}

class IndicatorLight {
  + type : String
  + isEnabled : Boolean

}

@enduml

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The design of the wet well control system shall provide for the safety and protection of pumping station operators, maintenance personnel, and the public from hazards that may result from its operation.

issues.description: The requirement is vague and untestable; it does not specify which hazards (e.g., electrical shock, chemical exposure, toxic gases, mechanical injury, drowning, equipment failure) must be addressed nor what specific safety measures are required.
issues.suggested_fix: Specify the types of hazards (e.g., electrical shock, chemical exposure, toxic gases, mechanical injury, drowning, equipment failure) and define corresponding safety measures (e.g., alarms, emergency shutoffs, interlocks, protective equipment requirements).

issues.description: No acceptance criteria or measurable metrics are provided to verify that safety and protection requirements are met for each identified hazard.
issues.suggested_fix: Define measurable safety performance criteria and acceptance tests (e.g., alarm response times, interlock functions, protective device activation thresholds) for each identified hazard.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The control system shall be responsible for monitoring and reporting the level of liquid in the wet well.

issues.description: "Monitoring" versus "reporting" are not differentiated; unclear what each entails and what interfaces/formats are expected.
issues.suggested_fix: Clarify monitoring method (e.g., continuous sampling, polling interval) and reporting format (e.g., alarms, data logs, UI display).

issues.description: Lacks information on the required update frequency and precision (e.g., sampling interval, resolution in feet).
issues.suggested_fix: Specify required sampling rate (e.g., once per second) and measurement resolution (e.g., 0.1 ft).

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The control system shall be responsible for activating a visual and audible alarm when a hazardous condition exists.

issues.description: The requirement does not define what constitutes a hazardous condition.
issues.suggested_fix: Enumerate specific hazardous conditions (e.g., high liquid level, pump seal failure, unauthorized entry, motor overheating, power failure) that trigger the alarm.

issues.description: Requirement overlaps with REQ-015 and RQ-032 which also specify alarm features, causing duplication.
issues.suggested_fix: Consolidate alarm activation requirements into a single requirement and reference it from other sections.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The control system shall be responsible for switching each submersible pump on or off in a timely fashion depending on the level of liquid within the wet well.

issues.description: The requirement uses the term "timely fashion" without specifying response time, and does not define specific liquid level thresholds for pump activation/deactivation.
issues.suggested_fix: Define maximum allowable response time (e.g., within 2 seconds of threshold crossing) and specify exact liquid level thresholds (e.g., lead and lag pump depths).

issues.description: Does not define level thresholds for pump on/off actions (e.g., lead pump depth, lag pump depth).
issues.suggested_fix: Reference or define specific level thresholds (e.g., link to requirements REQ-044 and REQ-045).

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide automated operation.

issues.description: Does not specify which aspects of operation are automated or the automation logic.
issues.suggested_fix: Define specific automated functions (e.g., pump control based on liquid levels, alarm activation, pump rotation for run-time equalization).

issues.description: Duplicate with REQ-017, causing confusion about the scope of automation.
issues.suggested_fix: Merge REQ-006 and REQ-017 into a single requirement and elaborate on specific automated functions.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide local manual override operation.

issues.description: Overlaps with REQ-016, which also calls for manual override of the site.
issues.suggested_fix: Unify manual override requirements (REQ-007 and REQ-016) and clarify different operation modes.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide local observational operation.

issues.description: The term "observational operation" is unclear; it is not defined whether it refers to read-only monitoring, diagnostics, or data logging.
issues.suggested_fix: Clarify what "observational operation" entails (e.g., read-only monitoring, data logging, diagnostics display) and specify requirements accordingly.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall start the pump motors to prevent the wet well from running over and stop the pump motors before the wet well runs dry.

issues.description: Does not specify the liquid level thresholds for preventing overflow and dry-run conditions.
issues.suggested_fix: Define specific liquid level thresholds in feet for overflow prevention and for stopping pumps before dry-run conditions occur.

issues.description: Thresholds for preventing overflow and dry-run are not specified; refer to requirements REQ-044 through REQ-046 for exact values.
issues.suggested_fix: Link to specific level threshold requirements (REQ-044 to REQ-046) or include threshold attributes directly.

issues.description: Overlaps with REQ-021 which assigns the same start/stop responsibility to the PumpControlUnit, leading to ambiguous component responsibilities.
issues.suggested_fix: Clarify division of responsibilities between WetWellControlSystem and PumpControlUnit for pump motor control and consolidate duplicate requirements.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall monitor the pumping site for unauthorized entry or trespass.

issues.description: Overlaps with REQ-030 which also assigns site monitoring to the PumpControlUnit, causing duplication of functionality.
issues.suggested_fix: Define a single system component (WetWellControlSystem or PumpControlUnit) responsible for security monitoring and remove duplication in the other requirement.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall monitor the environmental conditions within the wet well.

issues.description: Does not specify which environmental parameters to monitor (e.g., temperature, humidity, toxic gas levels).
issues.suggested_fix: Specify exact environmental conditions to monitor (e.g., temperature, humidity, methane gas levels, hydrogen sulfide levels).

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall monitor the physical condition of each pump for the existence of moisture and excessive temperatures.

issues.description: Does not define the threshold values for what constitutes excessive temperature or moisture levels.
issues.suggested_fix: Define specific sensor thresholds (e.g., moisture level detection settings and temperature >85°C) that trigger alerts.

issues.description: Thresholds for moisture and temperature at which a condition is considered excessive are not provided.
issues.suggested_fix: Specify sensor thresholds for moisture detection and maximum allowable temperature before alarms are activated.

issues.description: PumpControlUnit also monitors moisture and overheat conditions, creating overlapping functionality.
issues.suggested_fix: Clarify whether pump physical condition monitoring is handled by WetWellControlSystem or PumpControlUnit and consolidate monitoring responsibilities.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall display real time and historical operational parameters.

issues.description: Duplicated by REQ-037, causing two separate display requirements for real-time and historical data.
issues.suggested_fix: Define clear display responsibilities or consolidate parameter display functionality into a single control panel.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide an alarm feature.

issues.description: Duplicates REQ-004, which already specifies activation of visual and audible alarms for hazardous conditions.
issues.suggested_fix: Remove this requirement or merge its content into REQ-004 to avoid duplication.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide a manual override of the site.

issues.description: Duplicates REQ-007, causing redundancy in manual override functionality.
issues.suggested_fix: Merge REQ-016 into REQ-007 and clarify override controls and operation modes.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide automated operation of the site.

issues.description: Duplicate of REQ-006; introduces confusion about the scope of automated operation.
issues.suggested_fix: Combine with REQ-006 and elaborate on specific automated functions within a single requirement.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall equalize the run time between the pumps.

issues.description: Does not define how run time is measured or what tolerance is acceptable for equalization.
issues.suggested_fix: Specify the run-time equalization algorithm, measurement period, and acceptable run time variance.

issues.description: Duplicate of REQ-026 for PumpControlUnit, causing redundancy in run-time equalization requirements.
issues.suggested_fix: Merge equalization requirements for the site and pump control unit under a single responsibility and remove duplication.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The pump control unit shall start the submersible pump motors to prevent the wet well from running over and stop the pump motors before the wet well runs dry.

issues.description: Duplicates REQ-009, creating ambiguity about which component (WetWellControlSystem or PumpControlUnit) is responsible for pump motor control.
issues.suggested_fix: Clarify and assign exclusive responsibility for starting and stopping pump motors to one component and consolidate duplicate requirements.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: An alarm state shall be set when the high water level is reached.

issues.description: The requirement does not define the numeric threshold for 'high water level' nor specify how the alarm state is represented.
issues.suggested_fix: Define the exact liquid level threshold (in feet) that triggers the high water level alarm and specify the expected alarm state behavior.

issues.description: High water alarm functionality is also defined in REQ-046, causing duplication without clear separation.
issues.suggested_fix: Consolidate high water alarm triggers into a single requirement or differentiate float switch behavior from system alarm logic.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The starting and stopping of the pump motors shall be done in a manner that equalizes the run times on the motors.

issues.description: Duplicate of REQ-018, causing redundancy in run-time equalization requirements.
issues.suggested_fix: Unify equalization requirements under a single statement and assign responsibility to the appropriate component.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: Level switches shall be used to indicate when pump motors should be started.

issues.description: Does not define the level thresholds for switch actuation or how switch outputs integrate into control logic.
issues.suggested_fix: Specify switch actuation points and describe their connection to pump start commands in the control system.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The pump control unit shall be responsible for monitoring the pumping site.

issues.description: Duplicate of REQ-011, causing uncertainty about which unit handles site monitoring.
issues.suggested_fix: Assign pumping site monitoring to one component and update the other requirement accordingly.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: Monitor and detect prohibited entry to the wet well through the access door by way of broken electrical circuit. Both audible and visible alarms shall be activated.

issues.description: Duplicate of REQ-036 with identical functionality, resulting in redundant requirements.
issues.suggested_fix: Remove one occurrence and reference a common intrusion detection requirement.

issues.description: Does not specify response time or alarm duration for unauthorized entry detection.
issues.suggested_fix: Define maximum detection-to-alarm latency and minimum alarm duration requirements.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: Monitor and detect occurrence of a pump motor seal leak. If a leak has been detected, both an audible and visible alarm should be activated.

issues.description: Uses 'should' instead of 'shall', creating inconsistent obligation levels compared to other alarm requirements.
issues.suggested_fix: Change 'should' to 'shall' to maintain consistent requirement language for alarm activation.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: Monitor and detect prohibited entry by way of a broken electrical circuit. Both audible and visible alarms shall be activated.

issues.description: Duplicate of REQ-033 with slightly different wording, leading to redundant requirements.
issues.suggested_fix: Remove this requirement or merge it into REQ-033 and standardize the wording.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The pump control unit shall be responsible for displaying real time and historical operational parameters.

issues.description: Overlaps with REQ-014, creating duplicate display requirements for operational parameters.
issues.suggested_fix: Consolidate display requirements or specify distinct parameters for each control unit.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: When the depth of liquid is equal to or greater than the lead pump depth, the float switch shall set a state which causes the first pump to turn on.

issues.description: The requirement does not define the numeric 'lead pump depth' threshold or how to configure the float switch to trigger the pump.
issues.suggested_fix: Specify the exact lead pump activation depth (in feet) and describe the float switch configuration or signaling mechanism.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: When the depth of liquid is equal to or greater than the lag pump depth, the float switch shall set a state which causes the second pump to turn on.

issues.description: The requirement does not define the numeric 'lag pump depth' threshold or how to configure the float switch to trigger the second pump.
issues.suggested_fix: Specify the exact lag pump activation depth (in feet) and extend the float switch model to support multiple threshold-pump associations.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: When the depth of liquid is equal to or greater than the allowable high liquid depth, the float switch shall set an alarm state.

issues.description: The requirement does not define the numeric 'allowable high liquid depth' threshold or specify how the float switch communicates the alarm state.
issues.suggested_fix: Define the exact high-level threshold (in feet) and specify the signaling mechanism used by the float switch to indicate the alarm state.

issues.description: Repetition of high level alarm state setting overlaps with REQ-025, causing duplicated alarm definitions.
issues.suggested_fix: Combine with REQ-025 or differentiate float switch behavior from system-level alarm logic.

missing_requirements.description: Lack of comprehensive hazardous gas monitoring thresholds, alarm conditions, and ventilation fan control logic.
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall continuously monitor methane and other hazardous gas concentrations via dedicated sensors. Alarms shall trigger when methane levels exceed 25% of the Lower Explosive Limit (LEL) or other gases exceed thresholds defined by EPA regulations. The system shall automatically activate the ventilation fan when methane exceeds 10% LEL or any hazardous gas exceeds 50% of its alarm threshold, and deactivate the fan only after concentrations fall below 5% LEL for at least 10 minutes. Visual and audible alarms shall remain active until conditions return to safe levels and alarms are acknowledged by an operator.
missing_requirements.rationale: The domain model and external systems identify hazardous gas risks and include a MethaneSensor and VentilationFan, but no requirements define monitoring thresholds, alarm conditions, or automatic ventilation control; this is critical to prevent explosive atmospheres.

missing_requirements.description: Absence of temperature monitoring attributes and thresholds for pump motors.
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: Each pump motor shall be equipped with a temperature sensor that continuously monitors motor temperature. The system shall issue a warning alarm when temperature exceeds 70°C and automatically shut down the motor when temperature exceeds 80°C.
missing_requirements.rationale: REQ-013 and REQ-029 require monitoring for excessive temperatures and motor overheating, yet the PumpMotor class lacks a temperature attribute and defined thresholds, risking equipment damage and unsafe conditions.

missing_requirements.description: Configurable on-level and off-level threshold depths for lead and lag float switches.
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall allow authorized personnel to configure lead pump start depth (default 3.0 ft), lead pump stop depth, lag pump start depth (default 4.0 ft), lag pump stop depth, and high-level alarm threshold (default 5.0 ft) via the control interface.
missing_requirements.rationale: Requirements REQ-044, REQ-045, and REQ-046 reference specific depths but do not expose them as configurable parameters, and off-level thresholds are undefined, reducing flexibility and risking dry-run conditions.

missing_requirements.description: No specified data persistence, retention periods, or retrieval interfaces for historical operational data.
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall store operational parameters—including pump run times, alarm events, liquid levels, sensor readings, and environmental conditions—for a minimum of 90 days in non-volatile memory. After 90 days, data shall be automatically archived and retained for at least 7 years. The system shall provide query and export capabilities for historical data via the ControlDisplayPanel and remote interfaces, supporting filtering by date and time.
missing_requirements.rationale: Although REQ-031 and business rules require historical parameter recording for regulatory compliance, retention periods, archiving processes, and retrieval mechanisms are undefined, hindering reporting and analysis.

missing_requirements.description: Lack of alarm acknowledgment, silencing, and reset functionality.
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall require operator acknowledgment for all alarm conditions. Visual alarms shall remain active until the underlying condition is cleared and the alarm is acknowledged. Audible alarms shall be silenced upon acknowledgment but shall reactivate if the alarm condition reoccurs. All acknowledgments shall be logged with timestamp and operator identification.
missing_requirements.rationale: Multiple requirements mandate alarm activation (e.g., REQ-004, REQ-015) but do not specify how alarms are acknowledged, silenced, or reset, which is essential for effective alarm management and auditing.

missing_requirements.description: Undefined algorithm for lead-lag pump alternation and run-time equalization.
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall implement a lead-lag alternation algorithm whereby the pump with the lowest accumulated run time becomes the lead pump at each start cycle. The algorithm shall account for pump availability and alternate roles to equalize wear, ensuring balanced usage over time.
missing_requirements.rationale: REQ-018 and REQ-026 require equalizing run times between pumps, but the specific selection and alternation logic is not defined, risking uneven wear and premature failure.

missing_requirements.description: No defined system startup, initialization sequence, or periodic self-tests for components.
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: Upon system startup and at configurable intervals (e.g., daily), the system shall perform a self-test sequence including sensor connectivity checks (FloatSwitch, LevelSwitch, MoistureSensor, MethaneSensor), pump motor availability verification, alarm system and indicator tests, and communication interface validation. Failures shall be logged, alarms activated, and the system shall not enter automated mode until critical systems pass the self-test.
missing_requirements.rationale: Absence of initialization and periodic self-test requirements leaves latent faults undetected, undermining reliability and safety.

missing_requirements.description: Missing detailed communication interface specifications for external and SCADA systems.
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall provide SCADA-compatible communication interfaces (e.g., Modbus TCP/IP and OPC UA) to integrate with external applications including supervisory control systems, maintenance management, and regulatory reporting. The system shall transmit status updates at least every 30 seconds, respond to external queries within 2 seconds, and enforce secure authentication.
missing_requirements.rationale: Business rules require maintaining interfaces to other applications and context lists multiple external systems, yet no specific protocols, performance, or security requirements are defined, hindering integration.

missing_requirements.description: No requirements for sensor calibration tracking and maintenance scheduling.
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall track calibration dates and maintenance history for all sensors. It shall provide alerts when calibrations are due—float switches annually, temperature sensors every 6 months, gas sensors every 3 months—and prevent automated operation if a sensor’s calibration is expired.
missing_requirements.rationale: Critical operations rely on accurate sensor data, and absence of calibration management can lead to sensor drift, causing unsafe or inefficient operation.

missing_requirements.description: Unspecified performance and response time requirements for sensing and control.
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall sample all sensor inputs—including liquid level, environmental conditions, and pump status—at least every 500 ms. Actuator responses (pump start/stop, alarm activation) shall occur within 200 ms of the decision event. The system shall respond to alarm conditions within 1 s, update display panels within 2 s, and maintain a minimum 99.5% uptime during normal operations.
missing_requirements.rationale: Critical real-time operations require explicit timing constraints to avoid overflow, dry-run, or delayed hazard notifications.

missing_requirements.description: No mechanism for handling and prioritizing multiple concurrent alarms.
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: When multiple alarms are active, the system shall prioritize them in the following order: gas concentration alarms, high liquid level alarms, pump failure alarms, unauthorized access alarms. The highest priority alarm shall be prominently displayed on the ControlDisplayPanel, while all active alarms remain accessible in an alarm list.
missing_requirements.rationale: Without prioritization, simultaneous alarms can overwhelm operators and obscure critical hazard notifications.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement to detect primary power loss and switch to backup power.
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The wet well control system shall detect a loss of primary power supply within 100 ms and automatically switch to the backup power system, maintaining full monitoring, control, and alarm functionality without interruption.
missing_requirements.rationale: Continuous operation of pumps and alarms is critical for safety and compliance; current requirements overlook power failure and switchover logic.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for integration with the Sewage Grinder Unit.
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The wet well control system shall interface with the Sewage Grinder Unit to send start, stop, and status commands, and generate an alarm on any fault or jam condition reported by the grinder.
missing_requirements.rationale: The system context lists the Sewage Grinder Unit as an external system, but current requirements do not cover its control or monitoring, leaving gaps in overall system coordination.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for integration with the Valve Vault Control System.
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The wet well control system shall communicate with the Valve Vault Control System to open and close isolation valves upon manual override or emergency shutdown requests, and display valve status on the ControlDisplayPanel.
missing_requirements.rationale: Although the Valve Vault Control System is part of the system context, functional requirements do not address valve operations, compromising integrated safety procedures.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement to detect sensor communication failures or invalid data.
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The wet well control system shall detect loss of communication or invalid readings from any sensor (FloatSwitch, LevelSwitch, MoistureSensor, MethaneSensor) within 2 s and set a distinct sensor-failure alarm state.
missing_requirements.rationale: Assuming always-available and valid sensor data is unsafe; failures or invalid readings must be detected and alarmed to prevent unsafe operation.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for authentication and role-based access control for manual override.
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall require operator authentication (username/password or secure token) and enforce role-based access control before permitting any manual override of automated control functions.
missing_requirements.rationale: Unauthorized manual interventions could endanger personnel and equipment; security controls around override operations are missing.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for audit logging of critical control actions.
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall record all critical events—including pump start/stop, alarm activations, manual overrides, and power switchover—with user ID, timestamp, and event details. Audit logs shall be tamper-evident and retained for at least one year.
missing_requirements.rationale: Traceability for incident investigation and regulatory compliance requires comprehensive audit logs, which are currently unspecified.

missing_requirements.description: No usability requirements for display of alarms and operational status.
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The ControlDisplayPanel shall present a clear, color-coded view of active alarms, pump run times, and sensor readings, and include trend charts for liquid level and gas concentration to facilitate rapid operator comprehension.
missing_requirements.rationale: While parameters are displayed, readability and trend visualization are not addressed, reducing operator situational awareness.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for system scalability to additional pumps.
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The wet well control system architecture shall support the addition of up to eight SubmersiblePump and PumpMotor pairs without modifying core control software, including automatic discovery of new pumps at startup.
missing_requirements.rationale: Stations may expand; specifying scalability requirements ensures the system can accommodate additional pumps without significant redesign.

domain_model_issues.description: Requirements REQ-013 and REQ-029 specify monitoring pump motor temperature for overheating, but no TemperatureSensor class exists in the model.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add a TemperatureSensor class with attributes for current temperature, threshold temperature, and methods for temperature detection and overheating detection.

domain_model_issues.description: No dedicated AlarmState class exists to manage alarm logic, state transitions, and activation/deactivation as required by multiple requirements.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Introduce an AlarmState class (or Alarm class) to centralize alarm handling, including references to IndicatorLight, Buzzer, and state transition methods.

domain_model_issues.description: FloatSwitch only has one thresholdDepth attribute, but requirements REQ-044, REQ-045, and REQ-046 specify multiple thresholds (lead pump, lag pump, high alarm) and differentiation by pump role.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add multiple threshold attributes (e.g., leadPumpThreshold, lagPumpThreshold, highAlarmThreshold) or a pumpRole attribute linking to specific pumps; or support separate float switch instances for different threshold levels.

domain_model_issues.description: SubmersiblePump is missing pumpId and pumpType attributes needed to identify lead/lag pumps and support pump rotation and run-time equalization.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add pumpId (String) and pumpType (String) attributes to identify and classify pumps as lead or lag.

domain_model_issues.description: PumpMotor lacks temperature-related attributes required for overheating detection (REQ-013, REQ-029), currently without measurement capabilities.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add currentTemperature (Float) and maxOperatingTemperature (Float) attributes, or integrate a dedicated TemperatureSensor association.

domain_model_issues.description: WetWell is missing critical attributes for liquid level thresholds (leadPumpStartLevel, lagPumpStartLevel, pumpStopLevel, highAlarmLevel, overflowLevel) referenced throughout requirements.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add attributes leadPumpStartLevel, lagPumpStartLevel, pumpStopLevel, highAlarmLevel, and overflowLevel (all Float type).

domain_model_issues.description: No class exists to record and retrieve historical operational data, as required by REQ-014, REQ-031, and REQ-037.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add a HistoricalDataLogger class with methods for data recording, storage, and retrieval.

domain_model_issues.description: WetWellControlSystem duplicates monitoring and display methods found in PumpControlUnit, overlapping responsibilities and violating the single responsibility principle.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Refine class responsibilities to avoid duplication; remove duplicate methods from WetWellControlSystem and delegate pump-specific operations and display functions to PumpControlUnit.

domain_model_issues.description: PumpControlUnit contains methods overlapping with WetWellControlSystem (e.g., monitorPumpingSite, displayOperationalParameters, provideAlarmFeature), causing responsibility overlap.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Separate pump-specific control functions from system-wide monitoring and display; consider removing display and alarm responsibilities from PumpControlUnit.

domain_model_issues.description: IndicatorLight 'type' attribute is a free-form String, but requirements specify fixed types for pump running, seal failure, high temperature, and high level alarms.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Define an enumeration for indicator types or create specialized subclasses for each indicator state.

domain_model_issues.description: LevelSwitch lacks a thresholdDepth attribute required to determine actuation level (REQ-027).
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add a thresholdDepth attribute or extend the model to capture switch calibration settings.

domain_model_issues.description: Requirements REQ-028 and REQ-034 specify that PumpControlUnit should be notified of moisture detection, but no relationship exists to MoistureSensor.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add an association between PumpControlUnit and MoistureSensor to enable moisture detection notifications.

domain_model_issues.description: PumpControlUnit defines activateAudibleAlarm, but has no association to Buzzer, making it unclear how audible alarms are triggered.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add an association from PumpControlUnit to Buzzer to allow activation of the audible alarm.

domain_model_issues.description: ControlDisplayPanel is composed by both WetWellControlSystem and PumpControlUnit, implying multiple panels; domain likely requires a single panel instance.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Model a single ControlDisplayPanel owned by WetWellControlSystem and referenced by PumpControlUnit.

domain_model_issues.description: WetWellControlSystem.activateAlarm has no direct link to Buzzer, requiring indirect invocation via ControlDisplayPanel.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add an association from WetWellControlSystem to Buzzer or clarify that WCS uses ControlDisplayPanel to trigger audible alarms.

domain_model_issues.description: ControlDisplayPanel lacks an attribute to define the historical data period for display, as specified in REQ-014 and REQ-037.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add a historicalDataPeriod (String) attribute to ControlDisplayPanel to specify the time range of historical data displayed.

domain_model_issues.description: Modeling environmental conditions as a single String attribute is too generic; requirements may need structured data for parameters like gas levels and temperature (REQ-012).
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Replace environmentalConditions with a structured class or separate attributes for each environmental parameter to be monitored.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The design of the wet well control system shall provide for the safety and protection of pumping station operators, maintenance personnel, and the public from hazards that may result from its operation.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: Revise to include metadata and testable criteria. For example: Requirement: REQ-001 Version: 1.0 Priority: High Source: Safety Team Status: Draft Rationale: Ensure operator and public safety Actor: Wet Well Control System Action: Provide safety and protection Object: Operators, maintenance personnel, public Condition: During any control-system operation Acceptance Criteria: - When a hazardous condition is detected, visual and audible alarms activate within 2 s. - Alarms remain active until hazard is cleared and manually acknowledged. Dependencies: None. The wet well control system shall implement safety mechanisms including [specific safety features like emergency shutoffs, hazard detection, protective barriers] with response times ≤ [X] seconds to protect pumping station operators, maintenance personnel, and the public from operational hazards including [specific hazards like electrical, mechanical, chemical exposure].
requirement_completeness.rationale: Adding metadata, a clear operating condition, and acceptance criteria makes the requirement unambiguous, testable, and traceable. The current requirement is too vague about what specific safety measures are needed and lacks testable acceptance criteria.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The control system shall be responsible for monitoring and reporting the level of liquid in the wet well.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: Revise to include metadata and detailed monitoring specifications. For example: Requirement: REQ-002 Version: 1.0 Priority: High Source: Control Team Status: Draft Rationale: Ensure continuous level awareness Actor: Wet Well Control System Action: Monitor and report Object: Liquid level in wet well Condition: Continuously during normal operation Acceptance Criteria: - Liquid level is measured at least once every second with ±[X] inch accuracy. - Reports are logged and displayed within 1 s. Dependencies: REQ-001.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Defining frequency, acceptance criteria, and metadata ensures clarity and verifiability. It also lacks specific accuracy requirements, monitoring frequency, and reporting destinations.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The control system shall be responsible for monitoring and reporting the state of each pump and whether it is currently running or not.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: Revise to include metadata, update frequency, and test conditions. For example: Requirement: REQ-003 Version: 1.0 Priority: Medium Source: Control Team Status: Draft Rationale: Maintain real-time pump status Actor: Wet Well Control System Action: Monitor and report Object: Pump running state Condition: Continuously during operation Acceptance Criteria: - Pump state is sampled every 500 ms. - State changes are logged and displayed within 1 s. Dependencies: REQ-002. Additionally specify monitoring frequency, reporting accuracy, and destination (e.g., status updates every [X] seconds, 99.9% accuracy, report to display panel and maintenance logs).
requirement_completeness.rationale: Adding timing, acceptance criteria, and metadata makes the requirement measurable and testable. It also needs specific monitoring frequency, reporting accuracy, and destination specifications.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The control system shall be responsible for activating a visual and audible alarm when a hazardous condition exists.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: Revise to include metadata, precise timing, and alarm specifications. For example: Requirement: REQ-004 Version: 1.0 Priority: High Source: Safety Team Status: Draft Rationale: Rapid alert on hazards Actor: Wet Well Control System Action: Activate visual and audible alarm Object: Alarm devices Condition: When any hazardous condition is detected Acceptance Criteria: - Alarms engage within 2 s of hazard detection. - Alarm type and source are logged. Dependencies: REQ-001. The control system shall activate visual (red flashing LED) and audible (85 dB buzzer) alarms within [X] seconds when hazardous conditions are detected including high liquid level, pump failure, unauthorized access, or pump overheating.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Specifying timing, logging, and metadata ensures the alarm behavior is testable and traceable. It also needs to define specific hazardous conditions, alarm specifications, and response time requirements.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The control system shall be responsible for switching each submersible pump on or off in a timely fashion depending on the level of liquid within the wet well.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: Revise to include metadata, thresholds, and timing. For example: Requirement: REQ-005 Version: 1.0 Priority: High Source: Control Team Status: Draft Rationale: Prevent overflow/dry-run Actor: Wet Well Control System Action: Switch pump state Object: Submersible pumps Condition: When liquid level crosses defined thresholds Acceptance Criteria: - Lead pump turns on within 1 s of level ≥ lead threshold. - All pumps off within 1 s of level ≤ low-limit threshold. Dependencies: REQ-002. Additionally, specify threshold values (e.g., X feet for on, Y feet for off) and ensure switching completes within Z seconds.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Including precise thresholds, timing, and metadata ensures pump switching is predictable and verifiable. The term 'timely fashion' is vague and lacks specific threshold values and response time requirements.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide automated operation.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: Revise to define scope of automation and test criteria. For example: Requirement: REQ-006 Version: 1.0 Priority: Medium Source: Operations Team Status: Draft Rationale: Reduce manual intervention Actor: Wet Well Control System Action: Provide automated operation Object: Pump control cycle Condition: Under normal operating mode Acceptance Criteria: - System cycles pumps automatically based on level thresholds without manual input. - Automated logs are generated for each cycle. Dependencies: REQ-005. Additionally, specify automated functions (pump switching, runtime equalization, alarm management) and performance metrics under normal operating conditions.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Specifying the scope, conditions, and acceptance criteria makes the automation requirement measurable. The term 'automated operation' is too vague and needs specific definition of automated functions.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide local manual override operation.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: Revise to specify interface and safety constraints. For example: Requirement: REQ-007 Version: 1.0 Priority: Medium Source: Maintenance Team Status: Draft Rationale: Allow on-site manual control Actor: Maintenance Operator Action: Override controls Object: Pump operation mode Condition: When manual override is selected at panel Acceptance Criteria: - Manual commands take effect within 500 ms. - Override entries are logged and disabled upon system reset. Dependencies: REQ-006. Additionally, define available manual controls (start/stop pumps, acknowledge alarms) and safety interlocks.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Adding actor, interface details, and acceptance tests ensures manual override functionality is clear and verifiable. It also needs specific definitions of manual controls and safety considerations.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide local observational operation.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: Revise to define observational features and tests. For example: Requirement: REQ-008 Version: 1.0 Priority: Low Source: Operations Team Status: Draft Rationale: Allow local status monitoring Actor: On-site Operator Action: Observe system state Object: Wet well and pumps Condition: When system is powered Acceptance Criteria: - Status indicators update every 2 s. - Historical logs accessible via local display. Dependencies: REQ-014. Additionally, specify which parameters are displayed (liquid level, pump status, alarm state) and access controls.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Defining update frequency and acceptance criteria ensures observational mode requirements are measurable. The term 'observational operation' is unclear and needs clarification of observed parameters.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall start the pump motors to prevent the wet well from running over and stop the pump motors before the wet well runs dry.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: Revise to specify metadata, thresholds, and timing. For example: Requirement: REQ-009 Version: 1.0 Priority: High Source: Engineering Team Status: Draft Rationale: Prevent overflow/dry-run damage Actor: Wet Well Control System Action: Start/stop pump motors Object: Pump motors Condition: At defined high and low water thresholds Acceptance Criteria: - Pumps start within 1 s of liquid level ≥ high-limit value. - Pumps stop within 1 s of liquid level ≤ low-limit value. Dependencies: REQ-005, REQ-002. Additionally, define threshold values (X feet for overflow prevention, Y feet for dry-run protection) and response times.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Precise thresholds and test criteria make motor control behavior verifiable. It lacks specific threshold values and timing requirements.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall keep track of whether or not each motor is running.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: Revise to include update rate, logging, and data retention. For example: Requirement: REQ-010 Version: 1.0 Priority: Medium Source: Maintenance Team Status: Draft Rationale: Ensure accurate status tracking Actor: Wet Well Control System Action: Track motor running state Object: Each pump motor Condition: Continuously during operation Acceptance Criteria: - Motor state polled every 500 ms. - State transitions are logged with timestamps and stored for [Y] days. Dependencies: REQ-003. Additionally, specify accuracy objectives for status monitoring (e.g., 99.9%).
requirement_completeness.rationale: Specifying poll rate, logging criteria, and retention ensures tracking is precise and auditable. It lacks data retention and accuracy specifications.

reasoning.domain_model: We merged overlapping control functionality by consolidating the ControlSystem class into WetWellControlSystem, introduced a new WetWell class to encapsulate liquidLevel and environmentalConditions, and preserved Model 1’s detailed control and alarm methods. Conflicts in sensor and switch naming were resolved by adopting singular LevelSwitch and FloatSwitch, and indicator classes were unified under IndicatorLight and Buzzer. Relationships were kept consistent from Model 1, with the addition of the WetWell association, yielding a complete and coherent domain model.
reasoning.analysis:
Analysis aggregated using openai with specialized component processing:
- requirement_completeness: For each requirement I compared both LLM assessments, took the lower completeness score when they differed, merged all missing_elements entries into a union to capture every unique gap, and preserved the most detailed suggested_improvement and rationale text. Where suggestions were identical, they have been included once; where any unique insight existed, it has been retained.
- requirement_issues: We mapped each original issue type to the permitted types (Ambiguity→Incomplete, Testability/Missing Context→Missing, Misalignment/Conflict→Conflict or Inconsistency), preserved unique findings from both sources, consolidated duplicates by combining descriptions and suggestions into the most detailed form, and resolved conflicts by merging overlapping requirements or clarifying responsibilities. Each entry includes all distinct issues, unified where appropriate, ensuring consistency and completeness in a single, well-structured list.
- missing_requirements: Both source analyses were compared and found to contain identical sets of missing requirements. All 19 unique requirements were preserved and assigned sequential IDs. Similar duplicates were merged by selecting the most detailed text for each section.
- domain_model_issues: We merged the two sources by mapping identical element issues (e.g., FloatSwitch thresholds, PumpMotor temperature attributes) into unified entries, selecting the highest severity and most detailed descriptions and fixes. Overlapping class responsibility issues for WetWellControlSystem and PumpControlUnit were consolidated into single class-level Inconsistent entries. AlarmState and Alarm recommendations were combined into one Missing AlarmState entry with comprehensive details. Unique issues (e.g., SubmersiblePump ID attributes, LevelSwitch threshold, environmentalConditions attribute, historicalDataPeriod) were preserved. Relationship gaps (e.g., PumpControlUnit–MoistureSensor, PumpControlUnit–Buzzer, ControlDisplayPanel–PumpControlUnit, WetWellControlSystem–Buzzer) and attribute/class omissions were all included with clear suggested fixes and affected requirements lists.
